Sorry about the book but here is the point I wanted to make ğŸ˜‚ But the time is officially here. The core values that were put into the #StealthStandard are being applied to a brand new project.

Ironic that the token built on security would find their first task to be reviving themselves from a failed launch. But if they succeeded, it could go down as the greatest comeback and feat ever experienced in crypto so far.

Most people in crypto who get rugged will never see that money again. This was already a step up and was right in line with the projects original goals. One of them being help refund/revive rugs that occurred in the space. They also plan on paying the other 60% back as well.
THIS HAS NEVER BEEN DONE BEFORE. EVER.

Turns out that it only does take one or a few bad apples to ruin a perfectly good tree though. However, the team was able to recover some lost assets and after a long process of collecting wallets, etc. They were able to pay around 40% of the Eth back to the original holders.

But there is one thing that occurred. The team stayed true to there word and were transparent. They took a beating as well. Death threats, FBI and police being mentioned, just some crazy stuff that will probably be made into a movie one day ğŸ™ƒ

We were officially called a â€œscamâ€, â€œrugpullâ€, â€œhoneypotâ€, every other name under the sun. People were devastated, pissed off, and confused. The next 96 hours were a whirlwind of constant communication, investigation, and reconciliation for all.

On the 19th minute, the sell switch was flippedâ€¦ and all hell broke loose. A bot was able to get in on the 3rd buy of the launch for 10 Eth and was trying to sell like everyone else for the longest time. Once that switch flipped, the bot was the first wallet to sell.

Well, it was. The one Dev who wrote the contract had a few things that he didnâ€™t know he needed to do. One of those things was to have a switch flipped to allow holders to sell their tokens. Day traders were trying to get in and get out as the price rose.

The next thing I know, I check Uniswap and the price is shooting up. Up and Up and Up it went. I remember thinking â€œWhat the hell!! Is this really happening?â€ Within 18 minutes time, my $1250 shot all the way up to $8000. It really felt too good to be true.

After a few delays trying to perfect the contract, we were up and running. At the time, I was only able to put in about $1250 and I was ok with that. I had to start somewhere and it was a long term hold anyways.
Stealth was made up of such a large team, around 15 members, that were all so active at the time. Thank god for that or else people would have probably lost their minds lol. Ok back to the launch.

As launch day was coming upon us, activity in the TG began to increase exponentially. To the point that around when the time came, there may have been 2-3 times the amount of users ready for launch as there was for the entire month leading up to the day.

The tokenomics were also something that we have never seen before from a project. The value and hype behind stealth was slowly and organically building up just through telegram, twitter, and a few amaâ€™s. The belief and community behind this project were unbelievably strong.

The #StealthStandard was a baseline for people to believe that they were investing their money in a safe space. They had a plan to create a platform to vet and launch projects that would be safe from all of the rugs that were taking place in the space at the time.

On this day, â€œStealthâ€ was born. The vision for this project was simple. Do something that no other project in this space has ever done. They had a goal to be based around security, stability, and transparency in all aspects. A safe space for all, new or seasoned in crypto.

One day I came across a few of these people who changed their PFPs to this logo. So instinctively, I hopped into the telegram for this project when it only had about 30-50 people and had to see what it was all about. https://t.co/Vl8d91uW64

After a while, I started to see the same people always hanging out and shilling between the projects and started to keep an eye out for the moves that some of them made. This was around the time I really dove into crypto outside of mainstream exchange tokens.

Just wanna take a second to talk about my biggest horror story in this space. Late last year, I fell into the Mononoke and Hellsing Inu hype trains and was in TG all the time. Then again, who doesnâ€™t love their shitcoins at times ğŸ˜‚
